The Bellwind Collapse was the catastrophic failure of Akh'enet's undersluice infrastructure during the Ninth Meridian catastrophe's destabilization period.
Three simultaneous events defined it: aquifer backflow carrying saline surge into civic cisterns; resonance bells in court towers sounding continuously without human operation; mass ledger loss as archive vaults flooded and silted.
The continuous bell-ringing without human cause became the event's defining symbol: the institution's own warning system signaling its death.
The Jackal Balance Court interpreted the event as divine judgment and doubled down on descent rites; the Reed Ledger Wardens interpreted it as engineering failure and demanded emergency secular control.
Street conflict followed; caravan leagues withdrew permanent depots from Akh'enet's trade circuit.
Akh'enet did not die — it thinned: districts were occupied in fragments by groups preserving partial versions of old institutions.
The event severed the connection between Akh'enet's mortuary-legal function and practical governance.
The Reed Ledger Wardens survived as a functional institution; the Jackal Balance Court transformed into a ritualized remnant.
Surviving caravan operators withdrew from Akh'enet's formal circuits and developed alternative routes, contributing to the Cairn Wars period's route fragmentation.
The Bellwind Collapse's hydraulic effects were irreversible: the saline surge permanently altered the aquifer chemistry in Akh'enet's cistern district.
The event's name records both what happened (the bells rang in wind rather than by hand) and what it meant (the institution's signal function had become unmoored from institutional intent).

